\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {The Edenfield Police Department felt nothing like the rest of campus.}
\par\plain {Gone were the whimsical arches, the enchanted sconces, the scent of parchment and old spellbooks. Here, the walls were flat stone and the light was sterile, humming faintly overhead from charmed crystals embedded in the ceiling. The waiting room was too large and far too empty, its rows of bolted-down iron chairs left mostly unoccupied, their surfaces cold and uninviting.}
\par\plain {A steaming cup of tea would\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92ve felt absurd here. Even a fire rune would\u8217\'92ve died out from shame.}
\par\plain {Eddie sat forward in his chair, elbows on knees, hands clasped so tightly his knuckles had gone white. Across from him, Will tapped his foot, the soft }{\f0\fs24\i1 tick-tick-tick}{ filling the silence like a clock running out. Ashley sat between them, shoulders drawn in, her staff across her lap like a protective ward.}
\par\plain {Two Paladins flanked the stone archway into the main precinct\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 tall, gleaming figures in full white steel, faces hidden behind opaque visors. They didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t move. They didn\u8217\'92t speak. Just stood as if carved from the same walls they guarded, radiant symbols faintly glowing from the glyphwork etched into their armor.}
\par\plain {Besides them, there was no one else.}
\par\plain {Except Victoria.}
\par\plain {She sat apart\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 one row down, two seats to the left. A deliberate distance. She had her coat draped across her lap, hands folded atop it with eerie stillness. Her blazer still looked pristine. But the shadow under her eyes betrayed something closer to human.}
\par\plain {No one had said anything since they arrived.}
\par\plain {The air was heavy with grief unspoken. Questions without answers. The kind of silence you didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t want to break, because it might just shatter you with it.}
\par\plain {Eddie stared at the floor. A hairline crack ran through one of the stone tiles.}
\par\plain {He couldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t stop thinking it looked like the ones inside him.}
\par\plain {A voice crackled through the intercom on the far wall.\line \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Edward Welton?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s head snapped up.}
\par\plain {He rose slowly, the missing person paperwork clutched tightly in his grip. It was still warm from his hands\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 creased and smudged from where he\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d rewritten parts of it, over and over again, as if clearer words could change reality.}
\par\plain {Will gave him a nod. Ashley didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t speak, but her eyes followed him until he reached the desk.}
\par\plain {The reception counter loomed under flickering crystallight. Behind the reinforced glass sat a tired-looking officer in navy-blue robes, his badge dulled and his eyes glazed with bureaucratic fatigue. Without looking up, he extended a hand through the opening.}
\par\plain {Eddie passed the form through.}
\par\plain {The officer glanced over the details, flipped a few pages, then sighed and reached for a stamp. A dull }{\f0\fs24\i1 thud}{ echoed as red ink met parchment.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93We\u8217\'92ve logged the case,\u8221\'94 the man said flatly. \u8220\'93Estimated processing time is one month.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93A month? But\u8230\'85 she is missing today.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93We\u8217\'92ve got over three hundred active missing persons reports,\u8221\'94 the officer said, finally looking at him. \u8220\'93You\u8217\'92ll be contacted when a field detective is assigned.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That\u8217\'92s too long,\u8221\'94 Eddie said, his voice rising. \u8220\'93She was taken. This isn\u8217\'92t someone who wandered off. This is different. They\u8217\'92re making Chimaeras. They're experimenting on people\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Chimaeras?\u8221\'94 The man scoffed. \u8220\'93Right. And maybe dragons are nesting in the west tower again.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Look, I\u8217\'92m serious,\u8221\'94 Eddie said, stepping closer to the glass. \u8220\'93We saw one. Someone\u8217\'92s continuing the research. They\u8217\'92ve got her.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {The officer\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s tone flattened. \u8220\'93The creation of Chimaeras has been outlawed for four hundred years. No confirmed sightings in three centuries. Every known text on the process has been destroyed or locked away in Council vaults. They don\u8217\'92t exist anymore, kid.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93But they do,\u8221\'94 Eddie said, louder now. \u8220\'93I\u8217\'92ve seen one. Madeleine\u8217\'92s missing. Her wand was left behind. There were signs of a struggle. We don\u8217\'92t have a month. She doesn\u8217\'92t have a month\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Look,\u8221\'94 the man snapped, tapping the form with one ink-stained finger. \u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m telling you what I tell every family that comes through this door: sit tight and wait your turn. We don\u8217\'92t have the manpower to chase fairy tales. You want help? Get in line.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie stood there, chest heaving, a bitter heat rising in his throat.}
\par\plain {The officer let out a tired huff and leaned back in his chair. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Is there anything else,\u8221\'94 he asked, voice thick with boredom, \u8220\'93or are you just going to stand there?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie stared at him for a beat longer\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 jaw clenched, knuckles white at his sides\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 then turned without a word.}
\par\plain {His footsteps echoed down the polished stone floor as he walked back into the waiting room. The two paladins guarding the doors didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t flinch. They stood motionless in their gleaming armor, visors down, like statues of judgment watching over a tomb.}
\par\plain {Ashley and Will looked up from their seats, expectant\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 but Eddie didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t meet their eyes.}
\par\plain {Victoria spoke before anyone else could.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You won\u8217\'92t get anywhere with them,\u8221\'94 she said quietly. \u8220\'93Not with the police. Not with a case like this.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t respond. Not right away.}
\par\plain {He just walked past her.}
\par\plain {Through the heavy oak doors. Down the pale marble steps of the Edenfield Police Department.}
\par\plain {And into the cold, sleepless city night.}
