\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Eddie sat slumped against the cold stone wall just outside the police department, legs drawn up, arms limp at his sides. The sharp night wind tugged at his jacket, but he didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t move. Didn\u8217\'92t shiver. Didn\u8217\'92t speak. His eyes stared ahead, glassy and hollow, reflecting nothing but streetlight and the faraway haze of passing carriages.}
\par\plain {He looked like someone who\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d already buried what mattered.}
\par\plain {The heavy doors creaked open behind him.}
\par\plain {Ashley stepped out first, followed by Will. Their footsteps slowed when they saw him on the ground.}
\par\plain {Ashley\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s brow furrowed. She looked down at him, voice tight. \u8220\'93That\u8217\'92s it?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t move.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92re just going to sit here?\u8221\'94 she pressed, sharper now. \u8220\'93Let them do nothing? Let her be gone?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Will glanced between them, uneasy, but stayed quiet.}
\par\plain {Eddie didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t move. \u8220\'93The police said it themselves. They\u8217\'92re overwhelmed. Missing people all over the place. If even they can\u8217\'92t help... what chance do we have?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Will lingered behind her, unusually silent.}
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93She\u8217\'92s gone, Ashley.\u8221\'94 }{Eddie said, letting his head fall back against the stone wall, eyes closing. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s over,\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {Ashley stared at him\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 then dropped to a crouch in front of him, eyes fierce and unwavering. Her staff was still clutched tight in one hand like a torch not yet snuffed.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No,\u8221\'94 she said. \u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s not over.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What?\u8221\'94 Eddie asked back, \u8220\'93What did you just said?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I said, it is not over.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Come on,\u8221\'94 Eddie said. His voice was low and hoarse, but angry now. \u8220\'93Don\u8217\'92t give me that nonsense. Don\u8217\'92t you see that we\u8217\'92re standing inside a building full of knights and mages trained to uphold the law. }{\f0\fs24\i1 Do you see justice served in that building?}{\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Ashley\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s mouth parted slightly, but he didn\u8217\'92t stop.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You think if we just }{\f0\fs24\i1 try hard enough}{ we\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92ll find her?\u8221\'94 His voice cracked. \u8220\'93That we can just charge off into the night and save her like some a hero?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Will stayed behind them, his expression unreadable.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92re not being realistic. You're talking like someone who thinks justice always wins if you just }{\f0\fs24\i1 want it hard enough}{. }{\f0\fs24\i1 When you scream enough.}{ But justice doesn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t come because we }{\f0\fs24\i1 believe}{ in it. It comes with power, with reach\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 and we don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t have any of that. We\u8217\'92re just bunch of fucking kids. So let it go, Ashley. We\u8217\'92re not going anywhere with this, It\u8217\'92s over.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Ashley leaned closer, the wind tousling her wavy brunette hair with blond fades, eyes burning with quiet defiance.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93If you give up. If }{\f0\fs24\i1 we}{ give up. Then we\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92ve lost. We will }{\f0\fs24\i1 lose}{ Madeleine.\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94 Her voice caught\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 just for a moment\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 but she didn\u8217\'92t look away. \u8220\'93But we haven\u8217\'92t yet.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That\u8217\'92s what they want us to do,\u8221\'94 she continued, voice burning now. \u8220\'93Wait. Fade. Let the fire go out. But we don\u8217\'92t have to. We don\u8217\'92t have to wait for permission to fight for her.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie looked at her, something fragile flickering in his eyes.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You said there\u8217\'92s no hope,\u8221\'94 she continued. \u8220\'93But there is. There\u8217\'92s still }{\f0\fs24\i1 us.}{ We saw what happened. We know who took her. That\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s more than enough to start.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You don\u8217\'92t know what\u8217\'92s out there, Ashley.\u8221\'94 Eddie said, \u8220\'93If they can create a Chimaera, god knows what else can they do\u8230\'85 and you think we can go against something like that?\u8221\'94}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 She stood, her voice steady and resolute when she said:}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\i1 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s not over if you deem it is not over.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {The words hit Eddie like a pulse through the chest. He\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d heard them once before\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 different place, different pain.}
\par\plain {He hadn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t expected to hear them again. }
\par\plain {Not halfway across the continent. In a city so far removed from the corner of the world. And most of all.}
\par\plain {He hadn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t expected to hear them from }{\f0\fs24\i1 Ashley}{.}
\par\plain {Those words. }{\f0\fs24\i1 Her words}{ had pushed him to stand when he wanted to fall and stay on the ground a few years ago.}
\par\plain {And now, in some strange, fractured way, she was still pushing him. Not in flesh and voice, but through Ashley, of all people.}
\par\plain {Through the echo of a creed he\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d thought was buried.}
\par\plain {A laugh escaped Eddie\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s throat\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 more morbid than amused. It was ironic. }
\par\plain {He looked at Ashley\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 her eyes steady, her resolve burning\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 and in that moment, the old promise rang out louder than the despair threatening to drown him.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\i1 Damn you, Catherine.}{ Eddie thought. }{\f0\fs24\i1 You never leave me alone, huh.}
\par\plain {He tried to rise, muscles stiff and heavy, like dragging himself out of quicksand.}
\par\plain {Will and Ashley didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t hesitate\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 they each reached out a hand to steady him.}
\par\plain {Eddie grasped them, letting their strength pull him upright.}
\par\plain {He wiped a hand over his face, eyes searching Ashley\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s with a flicker of reluctant hope.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93So,\u8221\'94 he said, voice rough but steadying, \u8220\'93What\u8217\'92s the plan? If you\u8217\'92re the one who\u8217\'92s not giving up, I\u8217\'92m betting you\u8217\'92ve got a few tricks left up your sleeve.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Ashley\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s gaze sharpened, determination flaring.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93We\u8217\'92re going to need help moving this faster,\u8221\'94 she said quietly, then looked over toward Victoria, who was standing nearby, arms crossed but watching intently.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Then we need a help from her,\u8221\'94 Ashley said, \u8220\'93Her father\u8217\'92s the police chief. Maybe he can push things along, make sure Madeleine\u8217\'92s case doesn\u8217\'92t get buried.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eyebrows lifted. \u8220\'93Victoria?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Victoria folded her arms tighter, eyes cold. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Huh? Why would I? My father\u8217\'92s never around. He\u8217\'92s more interested in his own world than anything happening here. In fact, why would I want to do it for any of you?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Will stepped forward, cutting through the tension like a blade. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Come on, cut the crap.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {He didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t bother softening his tone.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t care how much you hate us. But there\u8217\'92s one thing I know for sure\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 you cared about Madeleine, I see that you are close friends to some sense. Maybe you hate how things went down with us, maybe you hate us, and you don\u8217\'92t trust any of us, but you love Madeleine. Just like we do\u8230\'85 Like we all do.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {His voice cracked with urgency, raw and unyielding.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93So put aside whatever disdain you have for us, for whatever grudge you\u8217\'92re holding onto. Help us get her back. Don\u8217\'92t do it for us, do it for her.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {The words hung heavy in the cold air, a desperate plea\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 and maybe the only chance they had.}
\par\plain {Victoria\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eyes flickered, something unreadable breaking through the walls she kept up.}}